  "inference": {
    "expression": {
      "kind": "cmp",
      "lhs": {
        "stat_id": "s_max_abs_partial"
      },
      "op": "<",
      "rhs": 0.02
    },
    "justification": "Single conjunct: max absolute partial Spearman across three mutation-class outcomes must be below 0.02. This is the falsifier-conjunct for the mutation-null claim. Outcome 'positive' here means 'the null IS observed' — TE density is not a mutational hotspot signature once GC is controlled. Note the asymmetry: a positive correlation > 0.02 would FALSIFY the null and trigger a separate 'TE density is mutagenic' claim.",
    "failure_mode": "If any partial |rho| exceeded 0.02, the mutation null collapses and the field's intuition that 'TE-rich regions are mutagenic' would receive empirical support. Observed max 0.002 — the null holds with substantial margin."
  },
  "conclusion": {
    "assertion": "After GC residualization, transposable element density does NOT predict somatic mutation rate at 1 kb resolution across PCAWG: partial Spearman rho with SNV rate = 0.000, with indel rate = 0.001, with SV rate = -0.002. The widespread intuition that TE-rich DNA is mutationally fragile is a composition (GC) artifact; once GC is controlled, TE density is null for mutation rate. This is the headline negative finding for paper_te_expression_atlas.",
    "formal": null,
